body:
Interesting. I see your point re robustness, but generally, I really don't like silent failures - even when logged. I'd much rather they throw so we can more easily detect and fix unexpected behaviour as early on as possible. There are 7 instances in this PR where we do this kind of assertion - would you only want to update it here or also in the other instances? I also understand that the current behaviour is that of silent failure, so I wouldn't want to break anything with this change - but as you mention, I don't think it does, given the `NoLimits()` parameter in all of these instances.

Cc'ing the other reviewers in case anyone else has a view (@w0xlt @glozow @theStack @aureleoules)

<details>
<summary>git diff</summary>

```diff
diff --git a/src/node/miner.cpp b/src/node/miner.cpp
index 0dc50c75c..c6838aee0 100644
--- a/src/node/miner.cpp
+++ b/src/node/miner.cpp
@@ -395,7 +395,13 @@ void BlockAssembler::addPackageTxs(const CTxMemPool& mempool, int& nPackagesSele
             continue;
         }
 
-        auto ancestors{*Assert(mempool.CalculateMemPoolAncestors(*iter, CTxMemPool::Limits::NoLimits(), /*fSearchForParents=*/false))};
+        auto ancestors_result{Assume(mempool.CalculateMemPoolAncestors(*iter, CTxMemPool::Limits::NoLimits(), /*fSearchForParents=*/false))};
+        if (!ancestors_result) {
+            LogPrintLevel(BCLog::MEMPOOL, BCLog::Level::Error, 
+                          "%s: CalculateMemPoolAncestors failed unexpectedly, continuing with empty ancestor set (%s)",
+                          __func__, util::ErrorString(ancestors_result));
+        }
+        auto ancestors{ancestors_result.value_or(CTxMemPool::setEntries{})}; // for robustness, continue with empty ancestors if the calculation failed
 
         onlyUnconfirmed(ancestors);
         ancestors.insert(iter);
```
</details>

_edit: now using `Assume()` in the diff as per MarcoFalke's suggestion_

